examples, both historic and recent, Jarret Lovell explores how seasoned protesters are handled and treated by the criminal justice system, shedding light on the intersection between the political and the criminal. By adopting the unique vantage of the street-level activist, Crimes of Dissent provides a fascinating view of protest from the ground, giving voice to those who refuse to remain silent by risking punishment for their political actions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCivil disobediencexUnited States. 0aCivil disobediencezUnited States. 0aCrimexUnited States. 0aCrimezUnited States. 0aSocial movementsxUnited States. 0aSocial movementszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  achange.  aconsequences.  acosts.  adeliberately.  afascinating.  ainsiders.  alook.  amotivations.  asocial.  astrategy.  aviolating.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081475227240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814753477.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814753477423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814753477/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK